=== TASK ===
# Bulk Upload Status

## Overview
Create a centralized Bulk Upload Status page for OfficeInventory AI that provides real-time visibility into batches of uploaded images. The page should display batches across lifecycle stages: pending inference, in-progress AI jobs, completed with results, and failed uploads with detailed error information. It should support fast filtering, searching, and drill-down into batch details (including per-item detections, confidence scores, and evidence). The implementation must guard against null/undefined values for all array operations, initialize state with proper array/object defaults, and validate API responses to ensure runtime safety.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
The Bulk Upload Status page is the primary cockpit for monitoring all upload batches. It aggregates batch records from the upload/capture layer and the AI inference layer, presenting a clear status narrative for each batch and enabling rapid triage of failures and review tasks. Goals include:
- Provide a tabular or card-based overview of all batches with key metadata: batch name, site/client, uploader, upload time, status, progress, and quick actions.
- Visualize batch status with color-coded badges (Pending, Processing, Completed, Failed) and concise progress indicators (percentage or step-based progress).
- Offer a Batch Detail Drawer or Side Panel per batch showing:
  - List of uploaded images (thumbnails)
  - Inference start time, current AI job status, and per-item detections with confidence scores
  - Evidence: cropped detections and source image references
  - Error details for failures, including stack traces or human-readable messages
  - Actions: Retry batch (for retryable failures), Cancel batch (if in-progress), and Mark for Review
- Provide Filter & Search capabilities:
  - Filter by status, site/client, date range
  - Text search across batch name, uploader, and site
- Ensure security and multi-tenant isolation per project context; display only batches accessible to the current user.
- Integrate with existing data models for uploads, batches, jobs, items, and errors (but no external API dependencies in MVP; design should accommodate future API wiring).
- Ensure a responsive, enterprise-grade UI with the project’s visual language and interaction patterns.

Key UI guidance:
- Batch List: Each row/card shows batch name, site, uploader, uploaded at, status badge, and a compact progress bar with a numeric percentage.
- Batch Detail Drawer: Expands from the row/card to reveal thumbnail gallery, AI job timeline, per-item results, and error details with a Retry button when applicable.
- Interaction: Hover states, micro-interactions on actions, and clear feedback to users after actions (e.g., toast or inline status update).
- Visual focus: Use accent lime green to highlight primary actions and active statuses; maintain high readability with the given color palette.

---

## Components to Build

- 1) BulkUploadStatusPage
  - Responsibilities: Orchestrate layout, fetch/process data, manage filters, and render BatchList or BatchCards.
  - Props/State:
    - batches: Batch[]
    - filter: { status?: string; site?: string; startDate?: string; endDate?: string; query?: string }
    - selectedBatchId: string | null
  - Behavior:
    - Debounced search input
    - Paginate or virtualize long lists (optional MVP)
    - Open details drawer for a batch
  - Accessibility: Keyboard navigation, ARIA attributes on interactive elements

- 2) BatchCard / BatchRow
  - Responsibilities: Display a single batch summary with status badge, progress, and actions.
  - Data: batch: Batch
  - UI: Title, site, uploader, date, status badge, progress bar, small status chips
  - Actions: View Details (opens drawer), Retry (if applicable), Cancel (if in-progress)
  - Safety: Guard all array/field accesses (use data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks)

- 3) BatchDetailDrawer
  - Responsibilities: Show details for a selected batch.
  - Data: batch, items: Item[], errors: ErrorDetail[]
  - UI: Thumbnail gallery, inference timeline, per-item list with detections, evidence, confidence, and an Error/Retry section
  - Actions: Retry batch, Cancel batch, Mark as Review
  - State: isOpen, activeTab (Summary / Items / Evidence / Errors)

- 4) ItemDetectionList
  - Responsibilities: List per-item detections within a batch
  - Data: items: Item[]
  - UI: Each item shows type, category, confidence, and evidence thumbnail
  - Safeguards: Guard array operations with (items ?? []) or Array.isArray(items)

- 5) FiltersBar
  - Responsibilities: UI controls for status, site, date range, and search
  - Data: current filter values, list of sites
  - Events: onFilterChange, onClear

- 6) DataDisplayComponents
  - ProgressBar: shows batch progress percentage
  - Badge: status badge with color mapping
  - ThumbnailGallery: renders batch thumbnails

- 7) NotificationToasts
  - Responsibilities: Show success/failure messages after actions (e.g., Retry started)

- 8) APIAdapters (MVP: local/mock data)
  - Responsibilities: Define TypeScript interfaces for Batch, Item, ErrorDetail
  - Functions: fetchBatches({ filter }), retryBatch(batchId), cancelBatch(batchId)
  - Validation: Ensure responses are arrays or default to []

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack: React + TypeScript (functional components, hooks)
- State management: useState and useEffect; lift shared state in BulkUploadStatusPage
- Type definitions (sample):
  - interface Batch { id: string; name: string; site: string; uploader: string; uploadedAt: string; status: 'pending'|'processing'|'completed'|'failed'; progress: number; items?: Item[]; errors?: ErrorDetail[]; }
  - interface Item { id: string; type: string; confidence: number; imageUrl?: string; evidenceUrl?: string; }
  - interface ErrorDetail { code: string; message: string; timestamp?: string; }
- Data safety:
  - Always guard array operations: (batches ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(batch.items) ? batch.items.map(...) : []
  - Use data ?? [] for API results; initialize state with []: useState<Batch[]>([])
  - Validate API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- UI Interactions:
  - Debounced search input
  - Filter chips/dropdowns for status
  - Date range picker (simple from-to inputs if no library)
  - Drawer opens on batch select; closes on backdrop click or escape
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard accessible controls, proper aria-labels
- Performance:
  - Lazy load images, avoid unnecessary re-renders; memoize item lists if needed

### Backend
- MVP API surface (for future wiring; provide stubs in codebase):
  - GET /api/batches?status=&site=&start=&end=&query= -> Batch[]
  - POST /api/batches/{id}/retry -> { success: boolean, batch?: Batch }
  - POST /api/batches/{id}/cancel -> { success: boolean }
- Data model notes (for future DB wiring):
  - Batches: id, name, site, uploader, uploadedAt, status, progress
  - Items: id, batchId, type, confidence, imageUrl, evidenceUrl
  - Errors: id, batchId, code, message, timestamp
- Validation: Ensure null-safe response shapes; return [] when no data

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - BulkUploadStatusPage requests batches with current filters.
  - BatchCard shows status and progress; opening a BatchDetailDrawer fetches or uses embedded batch.items and batch.errors.
  - Retry/Cancel actions fire APIAdapters calls; on success, refresh the relevant batch row or update local state.
- State synchronization:
  - After any action, re-fetch batch list or update in-memory batch object immutably.
- Error handling:
  - Graceful UI feedback on network or server errors; show toasts and inline messages.

---

## User Experience Flow
1) User lands on Bulk Upload Status. Page loads with a default view of batches (all statuses) and a visual balance of cards/list items.
2) User uses Filters Bar to narrow view by status, site, and date range; optionally types in search query.
3) User scans batch list; each batch shows status badge and progress. Hover reveals subtle focus; click on a batch to open Batch Detail Drawer.
4) Drawer reveals:
   - Thumbnail gallery of uploaded images
   - Inference start time, progress, and per-item detections with confidence
   - Evidence sections showing cropped detections and source imagery
   - Errors section with details and a Retry button if applicable
5) If a batch is failed or in-progress in need action, user clicks Retry or Cancel:
   - UI shows immediate feedback (loading state, toast)
   - After completion, the batch row updates to Completed/Failed status with updated progress
6) User can close the drawer, adjust filters, or navigate away; state persists in the current session as applicable.

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models:
  - Batch
    - id: string
    - name: string
    - site: string
    - uploader: string
    - uploadedAt: string (ISO)
    - status: 'pending'|'processing'|'completed'|'failed'
    - progress: number (0-100)
    - items?: Item[]
    - errors?: ErrorDetail[]
  - Item
    - id: string
    - batchId: string
    - type: string
    - confidence: number
    - imageUrl?: string
    - evidenceUrl?: string
  - ErrorDetail
    - code: string
    - message: string
    - timestamp?: string
- API Endpoints:
  - GET /api/batches?status=&site=&start=&end=&query=
  - POST /api/batches/{id}/retry
  - POST /api/batches/{id}/cancel
- Security:
  - Ensure authentication is present; user role checks before performing actions (Retry/Cancel)
  - TENANT isolation: data filtered per current user context; no cross-tenant data exposure
- Validation:
  - Response shapes validated: const batches = Array.isArray(res?.data) ? res.data : []
  - Initialize arrays safely: const items = Array.isArray(batch?.items) ? batch.items : []
  - Optional chaining for nested reads: batch?.items?.length ?? 0

---

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The page renders a list of batches with correct status badges, progress bars, and basic metadata.
- [ ] All array manipulations guard against null/undefined (using (arr ?? []) and Array.isArray checks).
- [ ] BatchDetailDrawer correctly shows batch items, evidence, and errors; per-item detections render without runtime errors when items are absent.
- [ ] Filtering, searching, and date-range filtering work and do not crash on empty results.
- [ ] Retry and Cancel actions are wired; successful actions refresh the corresponding batch in the list.
- [ ] State initialization uses proper useState([]) patterns for arrays; no useState() without defaults for arrays.
- [ ] API response shapes are validated; no direct access to possibly undefined properties.
- [ ] UI adheres to the provided color palette, typography, and layout guidelines; accessibility and responsive behavior covered.

